Investigate the issue internally and try to provide a workaround to see all files/folders that a user has access to.

Hello Kevin,

I'm glad to hear the FSAC scan completed successfully. it is important to note this job only collects file system events from activity monitor.  It is necessary to run FSAC Bulk Import to bring the results into the MSSQL database.

FSAC also does not collect permission data.  This is performed by 1-FSAA_System_Scans and to accompanying FSAA Bulk Import.

The page you are viewing is the Web Reports view of Enterprise Auditor - served by default on tcp/8082.

the access information center can be access by either selecting the Access tab at the top of this page, which provides limited administrative functionality but is sufficient for most security analyst needs.

The AIC can also be access on it's dedicated port, default is HTTP tcp/81 or HTTPS tcp/481 - HTTPS requires additional configuration.

Thank you,

Brandon West
Technical Support Manager
Phone: 1-949-407-5125 | Toll-free: 888-638-9749

Hello Kevin,

My name is Ian and I will be assisting you with your case.

From our call you are looking for information on file shares and user access.
To get this information, first you will need to make sure the FSAA scan is running and succeeding as seen in the screenshot below.



After the scan and bulk import jobs both run. You should be able to open the Access Information Center page (default port 8082)
From the AIC, you will navigate to resource audit.




From resource audit you will have the ability to expand the "File Share" node, and see all file servers that have been scanned. You can expand these file servers to find their shares and when selected, from the right panel, you can see the permissions on these individual folders, you can also drill down and see sub folder permissions as well.




If you would like to create a custom report inside Enterprise Auditor, you can use the report creation wizard detailed in the documentation below.

https://helpcenter.netwrix.com/bundle/StealthAUDIT_11.5/page/Content/StealthAUDIT/Chapters/09.Reporting/Creating_a_Report.htm

If you have any questions on any of this or need any help, please let me know and I would be happy to assist.

Thank you,
Ian Ranstrom

Hello Kevin,

I'm glad to hear the FSAC scan completed successfully. it is important to note this job only collects file system events from activity monitor.  It is necessary to run FSAC Bulk Import to bring the results into the MSSQL database.

FSAC also does not collect permission data.  This is performed by 1-FSAA_System_Scans and to accompanying FSAA Bulk Import.

The page you are viewing is the Web Reports view of Enterprise Auditor - served by default on tcp/8082.

the access information center can be access by either selecting the Access tab at the top of this page, which provides limited administrative functionality but is sufficient for most security analyst needs.

The AIC can also be access on it's dedicated port, default is HTTP tcp/81 or HTTPS tcp/481 - HTTPS requires additional configuration.

Thank you,

Hello Kevin,

My name is Ian and I will be assisting you with your case.

From our call you are looking for information on file shares and user access.
To get this information, first you will need to make sure the FSAA scan is running and succeeding as seen in the screenshot below.

[cid:image008.png@01DB9262.D860BB70]

After the scan and bulk import jobs both run. You should be able to open the Access Information Center page (default port 8082)
From the AIC, you will navigate to resource audit.

[cid:image009.png@01DB9262.D860BB70]


From resource audit you will have the ability to expand the "File Share" node, and see all file servers that have been scanned. You can expand these file servers to find their shares and when selected, from the right panel, you can see the permissions on these individual folders, you can also drill down and see sub folder permissions as well.

[cid:image010.png@01DB9262.D860BB70]


If you would like to create a custom report inside Enterprise Auditor, you can use the report creation wizard detailed in the documentation below.

I'm glad to hear the FSAC scan completed successfully. it is important to note this job only collects file system events from activity monitor.  It is necessary to run FSAC Bulk Import to bring the results into the MSSQL database.

The page you are viewing is the Web Reports view of Enterprise Auditor - served by default on tcp/8082.

the access information center can be access by either selecting the Access tab at the top of this page, which provides limited administrative functionality but is sufficient for most security analyst needs.

The AIC can also be access on it's dedicated port, default is HTTP tcp/81 or HTTPS tcp/481 - HTTPS requires additional configuration.

Hello Kevin,

I'm glad to hear the FSAC scan completed successfully. it is important to note this job only collects file system events from activity monitor.  It is necessary to run FSAC Bulk Import to bring the results into the MSSQL database.

FSAC also does not collect permission data.  This is performed by 1-FSAA_System_Scans and to accompanying FSAA Bulk Import.

The page you are viewing is the Web Reports view of Enterprise Auditor - served by default on tcp/8082.

the access information center can be access by either selecting the Access tab at the top of this page, which provides limited administrative functionality but is sufficient for most security analyst needs.

The AIC can also be access on it's dedicated port, default is HTTP tcp/81 or HTTPS tcp/481 - HTTPS requires additional configuration.

Thank you,

Brandon West

Hello Kevin,

My name is Ian and I will be assisting you with your case.

From our call you are looking for information on file shares and user access.
To get this information, first you will need to make sure the FSAA scan is running and succeeding as seen in the screenshot below.

[cid:image008.png@01DB926D.3D288D80]

After the scan and bulk import jobs both run. You should be able to open the Access Information Center page (default port 8082)
From the AIC, you will navigate to resource audit.

[cid:image009.png@01DB926D.3D288D80]


From resource audit you will have the ability to expand the "File Share" node, and see all file servers that have been scanned. You can expand these file servers to find their shares and when selected, from the right panel, you can see the permissions on these individual folders, you can also drill down and see sub folder permissions as well.

[cid:image010.png@01DB926D.3D288D80]


If you would like to create a custom report inside Enterprise Auditor, you can use the report creation wizard detailed in the documentation below.

https://helpcenter.netwrix.com/bundle/StealthAUDIT_11.5/page/Content/StealthAUDIT/Chapters/09.Reporting/Creating_a_Report.htm<https://urldefense.proofpoint.com/v2/url?u=https-3A__helpcenter.netwrix.com_bundle_StealthAUDIT-5F11.5_page_Content_StealthAUDIT_Chapters_09.Reporting_Creating-5Fa-5FReport.htm&d=DwQCaQ&c=RMnmm6VPZn6InKz70COhA6ljkuRx8qD28wOQIYh-aEY&r=GiuBQrnleKLC82Z4IkwkMKAJt2prLdNwZZrkLeiXkvc&m=T0b7lrESnfNCMWAnBBvjYm-KqgX2d-La8HYQSvwdgmqAt0RX0Ccb5Ew6EIDBr4BN&s=p7_uJaUXVW86Bq2bff08wIFN_2QH3a4my25fnY8Z16c&e=>

Hello Kevin,

I'm glad to hear the FSAC scan completed successfully. it is important to note this job only collects file system events from activity monitor.  It is necessary to run FSAC Bulk Import to bring the results into the MSSQL database.

FSAC also does not collect permission data.  This is performed by 1-FSAA_System_Scans and to accompanying FSAA Bulk Import.

The page you are viewing is the Web Reports view of Enterprise Auditor - served by default on tcp/8082.

the access information center can be access by either selecting the Access tab at the top of this page, which provides limited administrative functionality but is sufficient for most security analyst needs.

The AIC can also be access on it's dedicated port, default is HTTP tcp/81 or HTTPS tcp/481 - HTTPS requires additional configuration.

Hello Kevin,

My name is Ian and I will be assisting you with your case.

From our call you are looking for information on file shares and user access.
To get this information, first you will need to make sure the FSAA scan is running and succeeding as seen in the screenshot below.

From resource audit you will have the ability to expand the "File Share" node, and see all file servers that have been scanned. You can expand these file servers to find their shares and when selected, from the right panel, you can see the permissions on these individual folders, you can also drill down and see sub folder permissions as well.

Hello Kevin,

I'm glad to hear the FSAC scan completed successfully. it is important to note this job only collects file system events from activity monitor.  It is necessary to run FSAC Bulk Import to bring the results into the MSSQL database.

FSAC also does not collect permission data.  This is performed by 1-FSAA_System_Scans and to accompanying FSAA Bulk Import.

The page you are viewing is the Web Reports view of Enterprise Auditor - served by default on tcp/8082.

the access information center can be access by either selecting the Access tab at the top of this page, which provides limited administrative functionality but is sufficient for most security analyst needs.

The AIC can also be access on it's dedicated port, default is HTTP tcp/81 or HTTPS tcp/481 - HTTPS requires additional configuration.

Thank you,

Hello Kevin,

I'm glad to hear the FSAC scan completed successfully. it is important to note this job only collects file system events from activity monitor.  It is necessary to run FSAC Bulk Import to bring the results into the MSSQL database.

The AIC can also be access on it's dedicated port, default is HTTP tcp/81 or HTTPS tcp/481 - HTTPS requires additional configuration.

Hello Kevin,

I'm glad to hear the FSAC scan completed successfully. it is important to note this job only collects file system events from activity monitor.  It is necessary to run FSAC Bulk Import to bring the results into the MSSQL database.

FSAC also does not collect permission data.  This is performed by 1-FSAA_System_Scans and to accompanying FSAA Bulk Import.

The page you are viewing is the Web Reports view of Enterprise Auditor - served by default on tcp/8082.

the access information center can be access by either selecting the Access tab at the top of this page, which provides limited administrative functionality but is sufficient for most security analyst needs.

The AIC can also be access on it's dedicated port, default is HTTP tcp/81 or HTTPS tcp/481 - HTTPS requires additional configuration.

Thank you,

Hello Kevin,

My name is Ian and I will be assisting you with your case.

From our call you are looking for information on file shares and user access.
To get this information, first you will need to make sure the FSAA scan is running and succeeding as seen in the screenshot below.

[cid:image009.png@01DB9CC7.FB8405C0]

After the scan and bulk import jobs both run. You should be able to open the Access Information Center page (default port 8082)
From the AIC, you will navigate to resource audit.

[cid:image010.png@01DB9CC7.FB8405C0]


From resource audit you will have the ability to expand the "File Share" node, and see all file servers that have been scanned. You can expand these file servers to find their shares and when selected, from the right panel, you can see the permissions on these individual folders, you can also drill down and see sub folder permissions as well.

[cid:image011.png@01DB9CC7.FB8405C0]


If you would like to create a custom report inside Enterprise Auditor, you can use the report creation wizard detailed in the documentation below.

Hello Kevin,

I'm glad to hear the FSAC scan completed successfully. it is important to note this job only collects file system events from activity monitor.  It is necessary to run FSAC Bulk Import to bring the results into the MSSQL database.

FSAC also does not collect permission data.  This is performed by 1-FSAA_System_Scans and to accompanying FSAA Bulk Import.

The page you are viewing is the Web Reports view of Enterprise Auditor - served by default on tcp/8082.

the access information center can be access by either selecting the Access tab at the top of this page, which provides limited administrative functionality but is sufficient for most security analyst needs.

The AIC can also be access on it's dedicated port, default is HTTP tcp/81 or HTTPS tcp/481 - HTTPS requires additional configuration.

Hello Kevin,

I'm glad to hear the FSAC scan completed successfully. it is important to note this job only collects file system events from activity monitor.  It is necessary to run FSAC Bulk Import to bring the results into the MSSQL database.

FSAC also does not collect permission data.  This is performed by 1-FSAA_System_Scans and to accompanying FSAA Bulk Import.

The page you are viewing is the Web Reports view of Enterprise Auditor - served by default on tcp/8082.

the access information center can be access by either selecting the Access tab at the top of this page, which provides limited administrative functionality but is sufficient for most security analyst needs.

The AIC can also be access on it's dedicated port, default is HTTP tcp/81 or HTTPS tcp/481 - HTTPS requires additional configuration.

Thank you,

Hello Kevin,

My name is Ian and I will be assisting you with your case.

From our call you are looking for information on file shares and user access.
To get this information, first you will need to make sure the FSAA scan is running and succeeding as seen in the screenshot below.

[cid:image009.png@01DB9CD8.FD86A3D0]

After the scan and bulk import jobs both run. You should be able to open the Access Information Center page (default port 8082)
From the AIC, you will navigate to resource audit.

[cid:image010.png@01DB9CD8.FD86A3D0]


From resource audit you will have the ability to expand the "File Share" node, and see all file servers that have been scanned. You can expand these file servers to find their shares and when selected, from the right panel, you can see the permissions on these individual folders, you can also drill down and see sub folder permissions as well.

[cid:image011.png@01DB9CD8.FD86A3D0]


If you would like to create a custom report inside Enterprise Auditor, you can use the report creation wizard detailed in the documentation below.

Hello Kevin,

I'm glad to hear the FSAC scan completed successfully. it is important to note this job only collects file system events from activity monitor.  It is necessary to run FSAC Bulk Import to bring the results into the MSSQL database.

FSAC also does not collect permission data.  This is performed by 1-FSAA_System_Scans and to accompanying FSAA Bulk Import.

The page you are viewing is the Web Reports view of Enterprise Auditor - served by default on tcp/8082.

the access information center can be access by either selecting the Access tab at the top of this page, which provides limited administrative functionality but is sufficient for most security analyst needs.

The AIC can also be access on it's dedicated port, default is HTTP tcp/81 or HTTPS tcp/481 - HTTPS requires additional configuration.

From our call you are looking for information on file shares and user access.
To get this information, first you will need to make sure the FSAA scan is running and succeeding as seen in the screenshot below.
